Command Injection — Task-Wise Answers

Task 1 — Introduction
• No answers required (intro only).

Task 2 — Command Injection Basics

2.1 What kind of vulnerability allows an attacker to execute system commands from an application?
→ Command Injection

2.2 Which characters are commonly used to chain commands in injection?
→ ; (semicolon)

Task 3 — Testing for Injection

3.1 What character did you append to test injection (/etc/passwd read)?
→ ;
3.2 What file did you try to display to confirm injection?
→ /etc/passwd

Task 4 — Practical Exploitation

4.1 What is the flag when you successfully execute a system command through the vulnerable parameter?
→ THM{c0mm4nd_1nj3ct10n_w1n}

Task 5 — Mitigation

5.1 What mitigation technique reduces the risk of command injection?
→ Input Validation / Sanitization

Task 6 — Real-World Detection

6.1 Which log section helps you detect potential injections in HTTP requests?
→ Request Parameters / Query Strings

Task 7 — Advanced Exploration

7.1 If you try chaining multiple commands with &&, what is the second flag obtained?
→ THM{do_more_with_injection}

Task 8 — Reflection

• No direct answers — discussion of prevention and secure coding.
